<div class="lb on" data-lang="en">

<div class="hero">
  <div class="hero-grid"></div><div class="hero-glow"></div>
  <div class="wrap hero-inner">
    <div class="eyebrow">Founder · GL Framework</div>
    <h1 class="hero-name">Ping Xu</h1>
    <p class="hero-name-zh">徐萍</p>
    <div class="hero-titles">
      <div class="hero-title-item">International Social Policy Thinker</div>
      <div class="hero-title-item">Reform Strategist · Author of 50+ Books</div>
      <div class="hero-title-item">UN P5 Senior Economic Affairs Officer Roster</div>
      <div class="hero-title-item">Born in Taiwan · Based in Boston</div>
    </div>
    <p class="hero-pull">
      "Policy on the wall is not policy in the home."
      <span>政策掛在牆上，不等於政策進入家庭。</span>
    </p>
    <div class="hero-stat">
      <div class="stat-n">50+</div>
      <div class="stat-l">Books Published</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<section>
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">The Origin</div>
        <h2 class="stitle">A framework born from personal loss</h2>
        <p class="body-text">I grew up in Taiwan with the NHI card as a fact of life. You got sick, you went to the doctor. No one asked about insurance. No one made you pay first. That system — covering 99.9% of the population at a fraction of Western costs — showed me what correct denominator design looks like.</p>
        <p class="body-text">Then my mother had a stroke. The NHI worked. It gave her treatment, rehabilitation, and care. It did what it was designed to do.</p>
        <p class="body-text">But when she came home, she needed long-term care. That is a different system. And that system, we could never access. <strong>My severely disabled younger brother took on all the caregiving. Alone. Every day. For a year.</strong></p>
        <p class="body-text">He died of overwork.</p>
        <p class="body-text">Not because he wasn't strong enough. Not because we didn't try. Because the system that existed to help families like ours was designed in a way that families like ours could never reach it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">The Question</div>
        <h2 class="stitle">Why does structure determine who survives?</h2>
        <p class="body-text">My brother's death is not a data point. It is a structural verdict. The long-term care system in Taiwan — and in most of the world — transfers its true cost onto the most invisible resource it has: <strong>the family</strong>.</p>
        <p class="body-text">Family caregivers' time is not counted. Their physical labor is not counted. Their career destruction is not counted. Their psychological collapse is not counted. Their deaths are not counted.</p>
        <p class="body-text">When a system's functioning depends on invisible resources, that isn't design. That is cost-shifting. And the cost is always paid by the most vulnerable.</p>
        <p class="body-text">This is where the GL Framework began — not in a seminar room, not in a policy paper, but in the lived reality of what happens when institutional structure fails the people it was built to serve.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="band testimony">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:32px">Personal Testimony</div>
    <p class="tq reveal">"My brother died caring for our mother.<br>In that entire year, we never once accessed<br>the long-term care system."</p>
    <p class="tq-zh reveal">「我的弟弟在照顧中風的母親一年後過勞猝逝。<br>那一整年，長照系統，我們從來沒有用上過。」</p>
    <p class="t-body reveal">The GL Framework is not an academic exercise. It is the answer to one question: <strong>why do systems built to protect people fail the people who need protection most?</strong> And what would it take to build them differently.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="books">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="eyebrow reveal">The GL Framework</div>
    <h2 class="stitle reveal">Three Books, One Architecture</h2>
    <p class="body-text reveal" style="max-width:640px">Each book addresses a different layer of the same structural problem. Together they form a complete diagnostic and reform methodology.</p>
    <div class="books-grid">
      <div class="book-card reveal">
        <div class="book-num">Book One</div>
        <div class="book-title-zh">《百元護十元》</div>
        <div class="book-title-en">The Hundred-Dollar Guard for a Ten-Dollar Asset</div>
        <div class="book-role">Denominator Identification Layer</div>
        <p class="book-desc">Diagnoses the core misallocation: institutions spend lavishly to guard low-value throughput while leaving their highest-value capacities exposed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="book-card reveal">
        <div class="book-num">Book Two</div>
        <div class="book-title-zh">《好政策為何帶來痛苦》</div>
        <div class="book-title-en">Why Do Good Policies Cause So Much Pain</div>
        <div class="book-role">Structural Rebound Layer</div>
        <p class="book-desc">Examines why well-intentioned reforms amplify the pain they were designed to relieve. Introduces structural rebound: when interventions succeed at the symptom level but accelerate the underlying failure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="book-card reveal">
        <div class="book-num">Book Three</div>
        <div class="book-title-zh">《分母革命》</div>
        <div class="book-title-en">Revolution of the Denominator</div>
        <div class="book-role">Architecture Redesign Layer</div>
        <p class="book-desc">The prescriptive layer. Genuine reform requires redesigning the denominator itself — not adding resources to broken systems, but restructuring the fundamental logic of how finite capacity is allocated.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="band" id="cases">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="eyebrow reveal">Structural Diagnoses</div>
    <h2 class="stitle reveal">In the Field</h2>
    <div class="case-row reveal">
      <div class="case-num">01</div>
      <div>
        <div class="case-label">Massachusetts, USA · 2025</div>
        <div class="case-title">The Massachusetts DUA: When Automation Accelerates Failure</div>
        <p class="body-text">Massachusetts spent millions automating its unemployment system. Appeals backlogs grew <strong>nine times over</strong>. On-time payments collapsed to 49% — the worst in the nation. This happened while new claims were at a six-year low. GL diagnosis: <strong>denominator acceleration</strong>. Speed was applied to a broken classification logic, producing errors faster, routing them to appeals faster, depleting adjudicator capacity faster.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="case-row reveal">
      <div class="case-num">02</div>
      <div>
        <div class="case-label">Taiwan · Ongoing</div>
        <div class="case-title">NHI vs. Long-Term Care: Same Government, Opposite Outcomes</div>
        <p class="body-text">Taiwan's NHI covers 99.9% of the population at a fraction of Western costs. Its long-term care system is facing a workforce gap of <strong>67,000 by 2028</strong> and a financial model 97% dependent on tax revenue. GL diagnosis: the NHI succeeded because it designed the right denominator — a universal risk-sharing pool. Long-term care fails because it relies on an <strong>invisible denominator: the family</strong> — whose cost is never measured, until the family breaks.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="mission">
  <div class="wrap" style="text-align:center">
    <p class="mission-text reveal">"Government policy must not merely exist.<br>It must reach the people who need it most,<br>at the moment they need it most."</p>
    <p class="mission-sub reveal">This is the founding conviction of the GL Framework. Every structural diagnosis, every book, every case study begins and ends here.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">Background</div>
        <h2 class="stitle">Recognition &amp; Credentials</h2>
        <ul class="cred-list">
          <li><strong>Author of 50+ books</strong> on social systems, education, housing, and welfare reform</li>
          <li>Selected to the <strong>UN P5 Senior Economic Affairs Officer roster</strong></li>
          <li>International social policy thinker bridging <strong>East and West</strong></li>
          <li>Reform strategist with direct experience in <strong>government systems, welfare institutions, and public administration</strong></li>
          <li>Born and raised in <strong>Taiwan</strong> · Based in <strong>Boston, Massachusetts</strong></li>
          <li>Known for <strong>fearless clarity</strong> and a human-centered approach to systemic reform</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="pull">"The most expensive form of waste is not fraud.<br>It is spending a hundred dollars to protect a ten-dollar asset."</div>
        <p class="body-text">Ping Xu's work is grounded in a single conviction: that structural failure is not inevitable. It is designed. And what has been designed incorrectly can be redesigned.</p>
        <p class="body-text">The GL Framework is not a theory. It is a methodology built from decades of research, lived experience, and the structural analysis of real institutional failures — from welfare systems in Taiwan to unemployment agencies in the United States.</p>
        <p class="body-text">The goal is not critique. The goal is correct diagnosis — because you cannot fix what you have not correctly named.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

